  <div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>Is it necessary for data scientists or machine-learning experts to read =
research papers?</p>



<p>The short answer is yes. And don=E2=80=99t worry if you lack a formal ac=
ademic background or have only obtained an undergraduate degree in the fiel=
d of machine learning.</p>



<p>Reading academic research papers may be intimidating for individuals wit=
hout an extensive educational background. However, a lack of academic readi=
ng experience should not prevent Data scientists from taking advantage of a=
 valuable source of information and knowledge for <a href=3D"https://www.nv=
idia.com/en-us/glossary/data-science/machine-learning/" data-wpel-link=3D"i=
nternal" target=3D"_self" rel=3D"follow noopener">machine learning</a> and =
<a href=3D"https://www.nvidia.com/en-us/glossary/data-science/artificial-in=
telligence/" data-wpel-link=3D"internal" target=3D"_self" rel=3D"follow noo=
pener">AI development</a>.</p>



<p>This article provides a hands-on tutorial for data scientists of any ski=
ll level to read research papers published in academic journals such as<a h=
ref=3D"https://nips.cc/" data-wpel-link=3D"external" target=3D"_blank" rel=
=3D"follow external noopener"> NeurIPS</a>,<a href=3D"https://www.jmlr.org/=
" data-wpel-link=3D"external" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"follow external noop=
ener"> JMLR</a>,<a href=3D"https://icml.cc/" data-wpel-link=3D"external" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" rel=3D"follow external noopener"> ICML, and</a> so on.</p>



<p>Before diving wholeheartedly into how to read research papers, the first=
 phases of learning how to read research papers cover selecting relevant to=
pics and research papers.</p>



<h2 id=3D"step_1_identify_a_topic_" class=3D"wp-block-heading">Step 1: Iden=
tify a topic <a href=3D"https://developer.nvidia.com/blog/how-to-read-resea=
rch-papers-a-pragmatic-approach-for-ml-practitioners/#step_1_identify_a_top=
ic_" class=3D"heading-anchor-link"><i class=3D"fas fa-link"></i></a></h2>



<p>The domain of machine learning and data science is home to a plethora of=
 subject areas that may be studied. But this does not necessarily imply tha=
t tackling each topic within machine learning is the best option.</p>



<p>Although generalization for entry-level practitioners is advised, I=E2=
=80=99m guessing that when it comes to long-term machine learning, career p=
rospects, practitioners, and industry interest often shifts to specializati=
on.</p>



<p>Identifying a niche topic to work on may be difficult, but good. Still, =
a rule of thumb is to select an ML field in which you are either interested=
 in obtaining a professional position or already have experience.</p>



<p><a href=3D"https://www.nvidia.com/en-us/glossary/data-science/deep-learn=
ing/" data-wpel-link=3D"internal" target=3D"_self" rel=3D"follow noopener">=
Deep Learning</a> is one of my interests, and I=E2=80=99m a Computer Vision=
 Engineer that uses deep learning models in apps to solve <a href=3D"https:=
//www.nvidia.com/en-us/glossary/data-science/computer-vision/" data-wpel-li=
nk=3D"internal" target=3D"_self" rel=3D"follow noopener">computer vision</a=
> problems professionally. As a result, I=E2=80=99m interested in topics li=
ke pose estimation, action classification, and gesture identification.</p>



<p>Based on roles, the following are examples of ML/DS occupations and rela=
ted themes to consider.</p>



