<p>At this point, we=E2=80=99ve selected a research paper to study and are =
prepared to extract any valuable learnings and findings from its content.</=
p>



<p>It=E2=80=99s only natural that your first impulse is to start writing no=
tes and reading the document from beginning to end, perhaps taking some res=
t in between. However, having a context for the content of a study paper is=
 a more practical way to read it. The title, abstract, and conclusion are t=
hree key parts of any research paper to gain an understanding.</p>



<p>The goal of the first pass of your chosen paper is to achieve the follow=
ing:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list"><li>Assure that the paper is relevant.</li><li>=
Obtain a sense of the paper=E2=80=99s context by learning about its content=
s, methods, and findings.</li><li>Recognize the author=E2=80=99s goals, met=
hodology, and accomplishments.</li></ul>



<h3 id=3D"title" class=3D"wp-block-heading"><strong>Title</strong><a href=
=3D"https://developer.nvidia.com/blog/how-to-read-research-papers-a-pragmat=
ic-approach-for-ml-practitioners/#title" class=3D"heading-anchor-link"><i c=
lass=3D"fas fa-link"></i></a></h3>



<p>The title is the first point of information sharing between the authors =
and the reader. Therefore, research papers titles are direct and composed i=
n a manner that leaves no ambiguity.</p>



<p>The research paper title is the most telling aspect since it indicates t=
he study=E2=80=99s relevance to your work. The importance of the title is t=
o give a brief perception of the paper=E2=80=99s content.</p>



<p>In this situation, the title is =E2=80=9CDensePose: Dense Human Pose Est=
imation in the Wild.=E2=80=9D This gives a broad overview of the work and i=
mplies that it will look at how to provide pose estimations in environments=
 with high levels of activity and realistic situations properly.</p>



<h3 id=3D"abstract" class=3D"wp-block-heading"><strong>Abstract</strong><a =
href=3D"https://developer.nvidia.com/blog/how-to-read-research-papers-a-pra=
gmatic-approach-for-ml-practitioners/#abstract" class=3D"heading-anchor-lin=
k"><i class=3D"fas fa-link"></i></a></h3>



<p>The abstract portion gives a summarized version of the paper. It=E2=80=
=99s a short section that contains 300-500 words and tells you what the pap=
er is about in a nutshell. The abstract is a brief text that provides an ov=
erview of the article=E2=80=99s content, researchers=E2=80=99 objectives, m=
ethods, and techniques.</p>



<p>When reading an abstract of a machine-learning research paper, you=E2=80=
=99ll typically come across mentions of datasets, methods, algorithms, and =
other terms. Keywords relevant to the article=E2=80=99s content provide con=
text. It may be helpful to take notes and keep track of all keywords at thi=
s point.</p>



<p>For the paper: =E2=80=9C<em>DensePose: Dense Human Pose Estimation In Th=
e Wild</em>=E2=80=9C, I identified in the abstract the following keywords: =
pose estimation, COCO dataset, CNN, region-based models, real-time.</p>



<h3 id=3D"conclusion_" class=3D"wp-block-heading"><strong>Conclusion </stro=
ng><a href=3D"https://developer.nvidia.com/blog/how-to-read-research-papers=
-a-pragmatic-approach-for-ml-practitioners/#conclusion_" class=3D"heading-a=
nchor-link"><i class=3D"fas fa-link"></i></a></h3>



<p>It=E2=80=99s not uncommon to experience fatigue when reading the paper f=
rom top to bottom at your first initial pass, especially for Data Scientist=
s and practitioners with no prior advanced academic experience. Although ex=
tracting information from the later sections of a paper might seem tedious =
after a long study session, the conclusion sections are often short. Hence =
reading the conclusion section in the first pass is recommended.</p>



<p>The conclusion section is a brief compendium of the work=E2=80=99s autho=
r or authors and/or contributions and accomplishments and promises for futu=
re developments and limitations.</p>



<p>Before reading the main content of a research paper, read the conclusion=
 section to see if the researcher=E2=80=99s contributions, problem domain, =
and outcomes match your needs.</p>



<p>Following this particular brief first pass step enables a sufficient und=
erstanding and overview of the research paper=E2=80=99s scope and objective=
s, as well as a context for its content. You=E2=80=99ll be able to get more=
 detailed information out of its content by going through it again with las=
er attention.</p>



